<p>Given the actual context of alarming increasing prevalence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria [
 <xref rid="B11-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">11</xref>,
 <xref rid="B12-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">12</xref>], particular attention was oriented on developing new antimicrobial formulations. For example, extracts of acacia gum [
 <xref rid="B13-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">13</xref>,
 <xref rid="B14-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">14</xref>], cinnamon [
 <xref rid="B15-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">15</xref>,
 <xref rid="B16-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>], clove [
 <xref rid="B17-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">17</xref>,
 <xref rid="B18-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">18</xref>], cumin [
 <xref rid="B19-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">19</xref>,
 <xref rid="B20-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">20</xref>], lavender [
 <xref rid="B21-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>,
 <xref rid="B22-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">22</xref>], oregano [
 <xref rid="B23-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>,
 <xref rid="B24-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>], rosemary [
 <xref rid="B25-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">25</xref>,
 <xref rid="B26-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>], sage [
 <xref rid="B27-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>,
 <xref rid="B28-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>], tea tree [
 <xref rid="B29-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">29</xref>,
 <xref rid="B30-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">30</xref>] and thyme [
 <xref rid="B31-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">31</xref>,
 <xref rid="B32-materials-14-01612" ref-type="bibr">32</xref>] were reported as promising alternatives to combat the growth of planktonic microorganisms, as well as the formation and development of bacterial biofilms.
</p>
